\pard\f0\fs28  In the north, where subsp. ({\b a}) is tetraploid and subsp. ({\b b}) diploid, the distinction between them is obvious. In the south where diploid plants of subsp. ({\b a}) occur, the distinction is less clear.{\i  G. verum} hybridizes with several species of Sect.{\i  Leiogalium}, and includes numerous ecological and geographical races which have still to be classified. The rank of many taxa which have been described from the U.S.S.R., e.g.{\b  G. ruthenicum} Willd.,{\i  Sp. Pl.}{\b  1}: 597 (1798) ({\i G. verum} subsp.{\i  ruthenicum }(Willd.) P. Fourn.), {\b G. tomentellum} Klokov in Kotov, {\i Fl. RSS Ucr.}{\b  10}: 470 (1961), {\b G. borysthenicum} Klokov,{\i  op. cit. }471 (1961), {\b G. tenderiense} Klokov, {\i loc. cit.} (1961), {\b G. densiflorum} Ledeb.,{\i  Fl. Altaica }{\b 1}: 137 (1829), is doubtful.
